                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d552">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 738.3915/98.]</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister to Haiti</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 5, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Haitian Minister for Foreign Affairs says that full powers were originally
                    given to the Haitian Minister at Washington; but if the Department does not
                    consider them to be such, and will outline the powers it desires him to have,
                    they will be issued at once, as the Haitian Government desires a speedy
                    settlement of the boundary dispute.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Furniss.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
